First I want to start by recommending using `top` and `left` as your positioning properties. In your case you want to position an element *relative* to the parent. Using `top` and `left` can do that perfectly without any side effects.  

`margin` is primarily used to indicate the space between siblings, and also for positioning in a parent, for example when using Flexbox or CSS Grid, and can have some unexpected behavior like bleeding through the parent.

Calculate relative Top and Left in %.
====================================

For this example I&#39;ll show you how to calculate the values from pixels into percentages. To do this you must know **how large** the parent is and **where** the child is. First select both the parent and the child.
```
// Select the parent and child elements.
var parent = document.getElementById(&#39;parent&#39;);
var child = document.getElementById(&#39;child&#39;);
```
Get the dimensions of the parent element. `offsetWidth` and `offsetHeight` indicate the size of the element as seen on the screen in pixels.
```
var parentWidth = parent.offsetWidth;
var parentHeight = parent.offsetHeight;
```
Then get the position of the child *relative* to the parent. `offsetTop` and `offsetLeft` are the calculated positions in pixels of the child in relation to the parent element. Almost similar to the `top` and `left` values in CSS.
```
var childOffsetTop = child.offsetTop;
var childOffsetLeft = child.offsetLeft;
```
Now you have the **dimensions** of the parent and the **position** of the child.
Divide the position on each axis (X: left &amp; width, Y: top &amp; height) by the size of the parent to calculate the fraction. Multiply the fraction by 100 and you&#39;ll have the value in percentage.
```
var childOffsetTopPercentage = (childOffsetTop / parentHeight) * 100;
var childOffsetLeftPercentage = (childOffsetLeft / parentWidth) * 100;
```
This gives you the `top` and `left` values in percentages.
Set the values to child element to replace the pixel value to percentage. Don&#39;t forget to prepend the `&#39;%&#39;` string after the value to make it a percentage value.
```
child.style.top = childOffsetTopPercentage + &#39;%&#39;;
child.style.left = childOffsetLeftPercentage + &#39;%&#39;;
```

This is most likely happening because the way you are using Generics. Class C contains its child (private T d), so when you instantiated A, you inherit fields a, b, c and another instance of A&lt;A&gt;, which will also contains fields a, b, c. Not sure what you&#39;re going for here but if you want to fix this remove the Generics (private T d) from c.

