I can see two possible solutions here: using only generic class without inheritance or using inheritance without generics.

Classes `A` and `B` don&#39;t have to extend the class `C`. Those redundant properties get into JSON representation from the parent class (namely `C`).

```java
    public class C &lt;T&gt; {
        private String a;
        private String b;
        private String c;
        private T d;
    }

    public class A {
        private SomeObject z;
    }

    public class B {
        private OtherObject z;
        private Integer y;
    }

    // example of usage
    C&lt;A&gt; a = new C&lt;&gt;();
    a.setD(new A());
    // and so on
    C&lt;B&gt; b = new C&lt;&gt;();
    b.setD(new B());
    // and so on

```

The other way is to make `A` and `B` children of `C` which in this case doesn&#39;t have to be generic.

```java
    @JsonTypeInfo(
      use = JsonTypeInfo.Id.NAME, 
      include = JsonTypeInfo.As.PROPERTY, 
      property = &quot;type&quot;)
    @JsonSubTypes({ 
      @Type(value = A.class, name = &quot;a&quot;), 
      @Type(value = B.class, name = &quot;b&quot;) 
    })
    public class C {
        private String a;
        private String b;
        private String c;
    }

    public class A extends C {
        private SomeObject z;
    }

    public class B extends C {
        private OtherObject z;
        private Integer y;
    }

    // example of usage
    A a = new A();
    B b = new B();
```

